        <Parent_String>Spanish carpets by pattern [300233639], rugs by pattern [300187593], rugs (textiles) [300185749], coverings and hangings by form [300185748], coverings and hangings by specific type [300185832], coverings and hangings [300205012], furnishings by form or function [300037342], furnishings (works) [300037336], Furnishings (hierarchy name) [300037335], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Early Spanish carpets with three major types of ornamentation derived from Persian or Anatolian rugs, an octagonal-hexagonal design, stepped lozenges design, and star and lozenge design; they are often embellished with coats of arms, and incorporate non-Islamic motifs such as animal or human figures.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Alfombras españolas tempranas con tres tipos principales de decoración derivados de alfombras persas o anatolias, un diseño octágono-hexagonal, diseños de rombos escalonados, y diseño de estrellas y rombos; éstas a menudo se embellecen con escudos de armas e incorporan motivos no islámicos tales como figuras animales o humanas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Spaanse tapijten met acht- of zeshoekige ornamenten, of met trapgewijs geplaatste ruiten,of met een ster in een ruit; ook met wapenschilden en niet-islamitische motieven zoals dieren of mensen; motieven afgeleid van Perzische of Anatolische tapijten.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052478/Kinebanian, Perzische en Oosterse tapijten</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>早期的西班牙地毯，其三大裝飾類型源自波斯或安納托力亞地毯，分別為八角形－六角形設計、梯狀菱形設計與星星菱形設計。此種地毯經常飾有盾形紋章，且包含如動物或人像等非伊斯蘭教的紋飾。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
